"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/819892","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-01-17","<p>Our Smart Systems and Flexibility Plan set out a range of measures that are being taken to support the development of storage in our energy system by removing policy and regulatory barriers, opening markets and committing £70 million of innovation funding for smart systems, including storage. This innovation funding is on top of the £246 million Faraday Battery Challenge to help the UK become a world leader in the research, development and manufacture of batteries for electric vehicles.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/819892/answer",,,,,,"2018-01-17T14:39:39.37Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/819892/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/819892/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-01-10","Energy: Storage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what steps his Department is taking to support the development of the battery storage industry.","false","Biography information for Peter Aldous","Waveney","Peter Aldous","121964"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/819893","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-01-16","<p>As set out in our Smart Systems and Flexibility Plan, the Government is committed to ensuring that the market for ancillary services becomes more transparent and new technologies and players (including those on the customer side of the meter) are able to compete on a level playing field. Enabling this does not require legislative changes. The System Operator is setting out a roadmap of improvements on transparency and accessibility in ancillary services markets and, through its Power Responsive initiative, supports providers of new business models in accessing ancillary services markets.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/819893/answer",,,,,,"2018-01-16T15:12:11.387Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/819893/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/819893/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-01-10","Energy: Storage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, whether his Department plans to bring forward legislative proposals to encourage the development of an open market for aggregating and trading behind meter storage in ancillary services markets.","false","Biography information for Peter Aldous","Waveney","Peter Aldous","121965"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/819894","Home Office","false","2018-01-15","<p>A response will be sent to the Hon. Member’s enquiry by 19 January in line with published service standard of responding within twenty working days.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline  Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/819894/answer",,,,,,"2018-01-15T17:36:50.863Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/819894/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/819894/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-01-10","Members: Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, when she plans to respond to the letter from the Hon. Member for Bishop Auckland dated 19 December 2017 on an asylum case.","false","Biography information for Helen Goodman","Bishop Auckland","Helen Goodman","121966"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/819895","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-01-17","<p>The Department currently has no plans to make such an assessment.</p><p>The CMA (Competition and Markets Authority), as part of its investigation into the energy market, found that the GB wholesale markets were broadly functioning effectively.</p><p> </p>","Watford","Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/819895/answer",,,,,,"2018-01-17T14:39:15.29Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/819895/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/819895/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-01-10","Energy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment his Department has made of the potential merits of supporting the creation of energy markets similar to Nord Pool.","false","Biography information for Peter Aldous","Waveney","Peter Aldous","121967"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/819896","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-01-17","<p>In our Smart Systems and Flexibility Plan, we committed to define electricity storage in primary legislation as a distinct subset of generation when parliamentary time allows. This is an important commitment and one that we will honour.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/819896/answer",,,,,,"2018-01-17T14:40:15.003Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/819896/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/819896/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-01-10","Energy: Storage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, whether his Department plans to bring forward legislative proposals to define energy storage.","false","Biography information for Peter Aldous","Waveney","Peter Aldous","121968"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/819897","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-01-15","<p>I spoke to Dr Bruno Holthof, Chief Executive of Oxford University Hospitals NHS Foundation Trust, on Wednesday 11 January. We discussed how the Trust is not currently changing cancer treatment regimes for its patients, or considering any change outside the standards set out by the National Institute for Health and Clinical Excellence. I also sought reassurance from the Trust that it is communicating effectively to patients, families and staff that there are no changes to cancer treatment programmes.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/819897/answer",,,,,,"2018-01-15T17:45:06.753Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/819897/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/819897/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-01-10","Oxford University Hospitals NHS Foundation Trust","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, whether his Department has had discussions with Oxford University Hospitals NHS Foundation Trust on the recruitment and retention of specialist cancer staff in that trust; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Layla Moran","Oxford West and Abingdon","Layla Moran","121969"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/819898","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-01-15","<p>Employers across the National Health Service including those in Oxfordshire are responsible for tackling the causes of absence of their staff including stress and mental health related illnesses.</p><p> </p><p>The Department is supporting the NHS in tackling these causes of absence through its mandate with NHS England which has a Commissioning for Quality and Innovation (CQUIN) incentive programme<sup>1</sup> to improve staff health and wellbeing, and publishes the annual NHS Staff Survey.</p><p> </p><p>NHS England’s CQUIN programme should encourage trusts to, where appropriate, introduce new services for employees to give them the support they need including quicker access to mental health services.</p><p> </p><p>The NHS Staff Survey<sup>2</sup> helps trusts benchmark the percentage of staff feeling unwell due to work related stress in the last 12 months against their peers which should inform local improvement plans.</p><p> </p><p>The Department also commissions NHS Employers3, which is working with NHS England, NHS Improvement and Public Health England to help the NHS tackle the causes of absence due to stress and mental health related illness through advice, guidance and good practice as well as tools and resources such as their emotional wellbeing toolkit “How are you feeling NHS”.</p><p> </p><p>Notes:</p><p><sup>1</sup><a href="https://www.england.nhs.uk/publication/nhs-staff-health-wellbeing-commissioning-for-quality-and-innovation-cquin-2017-19-indicator-1-implementation-support/" target="_blank">https://www.england.nhs.uk/publication/nhs-staff-health-wellbeing-commissioning-for-quality-and-innovation-cquin-2017-19-indicator-1-implementation-support/</a></p><p> </p><p><sup>2</sup><a href="http://www.nhsstaffsurveys.com/Page/1006/Latest-Results/2016-Results/" target="_blank">http://www.nhsstaffsurveys.com/Page/1006/Latest-Results/2016-Results/</a></p><p> </p><p><sup>3</sup><a href="http://www.nhsemployers.org/your-workforce/retain-and-improve/staff-experience/health-work-and-wellbeing" target="_blank">http://www.nhsemployers.org/your-workforce/retain-and-improve/staff-experience/health-work-and-wellbeing</a></p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/819898/answer",,,,,,"2018-01-15T15:53:08.713Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/819898/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/819898/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-01-10","Health Services: Oxfordshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what steps his Department is taking to tackle the causes of absence of NHS staff in Oxfordshire due to (a) stress and (b) mental health-related illnesses.","false","Biography information for Layla Moran","Oxford West and Abingdon","Layla Moran","121970"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/819899","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-01-15","<p>I will shortly be writing a detailed letter to the hon. member for Oxford West and Abingdon addressing her concerns about chemotherapy treatment at Oxford University Hospitals NHS Foundation Trust.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/819899/answer",,,,,,"2018-01-15T17:51:02.703Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/819899/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/819899/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-01-10","Oxford University Hospitals NHS Foundation Trust","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, if he will meet with the hon. member for Oxford West and Abingdon to discuss the availability of chemotherapy treatment offered by Oxford University Hospitals NHS Foundation Trust.","false","Biography information for Layla Moran","Oxford West and Abingdon","Layla Moran","121971"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/819900","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-01-17","<p>Oxford University Hospital NHS Foundation Trust is currently meeting seven out of the eight national cancer waiting times standards. Oxford Clinical Commissioning Group is working with Oxford University Hospitals NHS Foundation Trust to improve waiting times performance and ensure national standards are met, including the 62-day cancer standard.</p><p> </p><p>Achieving the unmet 62-day cancer standard is a key objective in the Government’s Mandate to NHS England for 2017-18 and Next Steps on the NHS Five Year Forward View.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/819900/answer",,,,,,"2018-01-17T15:06:36.323Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/819900/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/819900/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-01-10","Cancer: Oxfordshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what steps he is taking to ensure compliance with the national cancer waiting time standard in Oxfordshire; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Layla Moran","Oxford West and Abingdon","Layla Moran","121972"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/819901","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-01-15","<p>Oxford University Hospitals NHS Foundation Trust continues to meet operational standards for providing cancer care to its patients. The most recent figures for Q2 2017/18 show:</p><p>- Two Week Wait from GP Urgent Referral to First Consultant Appointment: 96.9% (operational standard 95%);</p><p>- One Month Wait from a Decision to Treat to a First Treatment for Cancer: 97.0% (operational standard 95%); and</p><p>- Two Month Wait from GP Urgent Referral to a First Treatment for Cancer: 85.1% (operational standard 85%).</p><p> </p><p>We are committed to improving the capability and capacity of the cancer workforce in England. Health Education England (HEE) published its first ever Cancer Workforce Plan on 5 December 2017, setting out plans to increase the numbers working in cancer care, speeding up diagnoses and treatment.</p><p> </p><p>Macmillan Cancer Support are currently carrying out a Specialist Adult Cancer Nurse Census</p><p>to understand the current size and location of the specialist cancer nurse workforce. This will</p><p>enable HEE to develop a much more comprehensive picture of how many specialist nurses are working in cancer and what further action and investment might be required to ensure timely and good quality patient care and experience.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/819901/answer",,,,,,"2018-01-15T17:46:13.897Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/819901/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/819901/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-01-10","Nurses: Oxfordshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what assessment he has made of the reasons for shortages in chemotherapy nurses in Oxfordshire; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Layla Moran","Oxford West and Abingdon","Layla Moran","121973"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/819902","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-01-18","<p>Nearly all local government core spending power is un-ringfenced. This allows councils, who are independent of central Government, to manage their budgets in line with local priorities. Total Core Spending Power for local authorities in England is set to rise in real terms over the next two years, from £44.3 billion in 2017-18 to £45.6 billion in 2019-20.</p><p>This Government is committed to protecting the most vulnerable in our society and we have already taken several steps during this Parliament to help secure a strong and sustainable adult social care system. The Spring Budget 2017 announced an additional £2 billion funding in England to spend on adult social care in the short-term. This meant that, by the start of this financial year (2017-18), the Government had given councils access to £9.25 billion more dedicated funding for adult social care over the next three years.</p><p>While it is for local authorities to manage funding according to local priorities, the Government expects them to provide the right services to local communities, especially for the vulnerable and older people.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","South Derbyshire","Mrs Heather Wheeler","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/819902/answer",,,,,,"2018-01-18T17:37:42.113Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/819902/answer","Biography information for Mrs Heather Wheeler","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/819902/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-01-10","Supporting People Programme: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, what assessment his Department has made of the effect on the supporting people programme of the removal of ring-fenced funding from that programme.","false","Biography information for Dr Lisa Cameron","East Kilbride, Strathaven and Lesmahagow","Dr Lisa Cameron","121974"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/819903","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-01-15","<p>Universal Credit has been designed to be simpler than the benefits it replaces and provides support for young people aged 16-19 in full-time non-advanced education or approved training, through the child element paid to their parents. This can continue to be paid until 31<sup>st</sup> August following their 19th birthday.</p><p> </p><p>The criteria in Universal Credit aligns with the academic year to allow most young people still in education or training under age 20 to finish their course and to be supported under their parents’ claim to Universal Credit up to the point at which they would be able to claim in their own right. This will generally be at age18, if they meet the conditions of entitlement.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/819903/answer",,,,,,"2018-01-15T16:15:10.987Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/819903/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/819903/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-01-10","Universal Credit: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 21 December 2017 to Question 120356, what the reasons are for the Qualifying Young Persons criteria in Universal Credit not being aligned with the Qualifying Young Person criteria in both child benefit and tax credits.","false","Biography information for Derek Twigg","Halton","Derek Twigg","121975"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/819904","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-01-15","<p>The Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy continues to work closely with the Department for Environment, Food &amp; Rural Affairs on the Call for Evidence on extending the remit of the Groceries Code Adjudicator. We have carefully analysed all responses received and considered potential solutions to issues identified by respondents. We will be publishing a full Government response to the Call for Evidence shortly.</p>","Burton","Andrew Griffiths","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/819904/answer",,,,,,"2018-01-15T16:34:22.537Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/819904/answer","Biography information for Andrew Griffiths","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/819904/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-01-10","Groceries Code Adjudicator","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, pursuant to the Answer of 12 December 2017 to Question 117048 on Groceries Code Adjudicator, for what reasons the Department has not published its response to its consultation on extending the remit of the Groceries Code Adjudicator, which closed in January 2017, and when his Department plans to publish its response.","false","Biography information for Kerry McCarthy","Bristol East","Kerry McCarthy","121976"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/819905","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-01-15","<p>Long-term conditions, such as, urological conditions are currently part of my portfolio.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/819905/answer",,,,,,"2018-01-15T17:53:15.473Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/819905/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/819905/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-01-10","Urinary Tract Infections","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, which minister in his Department will have responsibility for urological conditions.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","121977"
